.TH greg.pl "1"

.SH NAME
.B greg.pl
- Global Registry Generator

.SH SYNOPSIS
\&./greg.pl

.SH DESCRIPTION
GReG is a small program designed to automatically generate transfur variant registries based on given Java class names. 

.B Files owned by GReG:

.RS 4
.I ./tmp/java/registry/*
- Template registry files. Curently:
.RS 6

.I InitEntities.java
.br
.I InitLayerDefinitions.java
.br
.I InitRenderers.java
.br
.I InitTransfurs.java
.RE 

.br
.I ./generated/java/registry/*
- GReG's output files. Currently:

.RS 6
.I InitEntities.java
.br
.I InitLayerDefinitions.java
.br
.I InitRenderers.java
.br
.I InitTransfurs.java
.RE 

.I ./tmp/variants.greg
as STDIN input.

.RE

.SH OPERATION
.br 
GReG begins it's work by scanning STDIN for variant class names, in a
.B slof(5)
file. Typically this is done by piping 
.I ./tmp/variants.greg
file into STDIN.

Once this is done, GReG validates it's input,
with 
.I ^[A-Z][a-zA-Z]* 
regex.

Next, if the previous step succeeded, the 4 registries are generated.

.PP
.B InitEntities

.RS 4
First registry generated is the entity registry. GReG begins by scanning 
.I ./tmp/java/reistry/InitEntities.java
file and storing it in memory.
Next, GReG figures out the variant names in uppercase variats and generates both registry objects and SpawnPlacementRegisterEvent calls.
During this step, GReG looks for the following strings:

.I /*PERL_ENTITIES*/
- gets replaced with registry objects
.br
.I /*PERL_REGISTER_SPAWNS*/
- gets replaced with SpawnPlacementRegisterEvent function calls.

Once this is done, GReG Then it writes the file to
.I ./generated/java/registry/InitEntities.java
file.


.RE

.PP
.B InitLayerDefinitions

.RS 4

GReG begins generation of ModelLayerDefinition registry by scanning
.I ./tmp/java/registry/InitLayerDefinitions
file, and storing it in memory.
Next, GReG figures out the model name, and then generates appropriate event regiter calls.
During this step, GReG looks for the following strings:

.I /*PERL_LAYER_DEFINITIONS*/
- gets replaced with event register calls

In addition, due to model names being predictable (for now) GReG also generates import statements and adds them as needed.
During this step, GReG looks for the following strings:

.I /*PERL_MODEL_IMPORTS*/
- gets replaced with model imports.

When this is done, the modified file is written to 
.I ./generated/java/registry/InitLayerDefinitions.
.RE

.PP
.B InitRenderers

.RS 4
GreG begins generation of renderer registry by scanning
.I ./tmp/java/registry/InitRenderers.java
file, and storing it in memory.
Next, GReG figures out the variant uppercase name, the renderer name and generates appropriate event calls based on that information.
During this, GReG looks for the
.I /*PERL_RENDERERS*/
string, and replaces it with the generated event function calls.

When this is done, the modified file is written to
.I ./generated/java/registry/InitRenderers.java
.RE

.PP
.B InitTransfurs
.RS 4

GReG begins generation of transfur variant registry by scanning
.I ./tmp/java/registry/InitTransfurs.java
file, and storing it in memory.
Next, GReG figures out the variant uppercase name and the variant lowercase name. Then, GReG generates appropriate registry objects based on that info.
During this step, GReG looks for
.I /*PERL_TRANSFURS*/
string and replaces it with the generated registry objects.

.RE

.SH NOTES

GReG assumes that the entity class obeys AT Init system, see
.B at-init-system(7)
for details,
otherwise GReG will generate errors if you use a different init system, for example: CMod Init System.

GReG has no idea about gendered variants, as this is the job of
.B geng.pl(1).

